ns, conscious of the fact that they were metaphorically bearing Christ in their hearts. A later, over-literal interpretation of the name gave rise to the legend of a saint who actually bore the Christ-child over a stream; he is regarded as the patron of travellers. In England the name was uncommon in the Middle Ages, but became very popular in the 16th century, especially in parts of the North."],"variants":[{"name":"Kristopher","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: respelling of   Christopher ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Christopher de Berneval I, Knight was born about 1370, in Diocese of Meath, Ireland, his father, Sir Nicholas de Berneval, Earl of Ulster, was 31 and his mother, Joan Clifford, was 42. He married Eleanor Rochford in 1385, in Ireland. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died about 1400, in Diocese of Meath, Ireland, at the age of 32."},"et":{"Abt 1370–Abt 1400":"umbes 1370–umbes 1400","1357–Male":"1357–Surnud","1370–1400":"1370–1400","1370–1398":"1370–1398","1385–Male":"1385–Surnud","1390–1446":"1390–1446","1398–1433":"1398–1433","1340–1386":"1340–1386","1329–1382":"1329–1382","before 1357":"enne 1357","1385":"1385","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","Abt 1400":"umbes 1400","1370":"1370","1390":"1390","1446":"1446","Abt 1370":"umbes 1370","1357":"1357","1433":"1433","1400":"1400","1398":"1398","1386":"1386","after 1385":"pärast 1385","after 1398":"pärast 1398","1329":"1329","Ireland":"Iirimaa","Crickstown, County Meath, Ireland":"Crickstown, County Meath, Iirimaa","Diocese of Meath, Leinster, Ireland":"Diocese of Meath, Iirimaa","Crickstown Castle, Trimblestown, Meath, Leinster, Ireland":"Ireland, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Crickstown, Dunshaughlin, County Meath, Ireland":"Crickstown, Dunshaughlin, County Meath, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"Abt 1370–Abt 1400":"noin 1370–noin 1400","1357–Male":"1357–Kuollut","1370–1400":"1370–1400","1370–1398":"1370–1398","1385–Male":"1385–Kuollut","1390–1446":"1390–1446","1398–1433":"1398–1433","1340–1386":"1340–1386","132